GitHub Integration with Jenkins

We integrate GitHub with Jenkins so Jenkins can securely access the source code and automatically trigger pipelines whenever developers push code to the GitHub repository.

1. Install Required Plugins

   - Manage Jenkins → Plugins

   - Install:

     - Git Plugin

     - GitHub Plugin

2. Generate GitHub Personal Access Token (PAT)

   - GitHub → Settings → Developer Settings

   - Personal Access Tokens → Generate New Token

   - Grant Repository permissions.

   - Copy the generated token.

3. Add GitHub Credentials in Jenkins

   - Manage Jenkins → Credentials

   - Global → Add Credentials

   - Kind: Username with Password

   - Username: GitHub Username

   - Password: Personal Access Token (PAT)

   - ID: github-creds

4. Create a Jenkins Pipeline Job

   - New Item → Pipeline

   - Pipeline Definition → Pipeline script from SCM

   - SCM → Git

5. Configure Git Repository

   - Repository URL:
https://github.com/<username>/<repository>.git

   - Credentials:

     github-creds

   - Branch:

     main

   - Script Path:

     Jenkinsfile

6. Configure GitHub Webhook (Recommended)

   - GitHub Repository → Settings → Webhooks

   - Add Webhook

   - Payload URL:

     http://<jenkins-url>/github-webhook/

   - Content Type:

     application/json

   - Events:

     Just the push event

7. Configure Build Trigger in Jenkins

   - Open Jenkins Job → Configure

   - Build Triggers

   - Enable:

     GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling

8. Pipeline Execution

   - Developer pushes code to GitHub.

   - GitHub sends a webhook to Jenkins.

   - Jenkins pulls the latest source code using the configured credentials.

   - Jenkins executes the Jenkinsfile and starts the CI/CD pipeline.
 
